=> Java Commands Reference

    -> Check installed Java version
        -> java -version
        -> Example:
             java -version

    -> Check installed Java compiler version
        -> javac -version
        -> Example:
             javac -version

    -> Compile Java source file
        -> Syntax:
             javac <FileName.java>
        -> Example:
             javac HelloWorld.java
        -> Output:
             HelloWorld.class

    -> Compile and place generated .class files in a specific directory
        -> Syntax:
             javac -d <directory> <FileName.java>
        -> Example:
             javac -d out HelloWorld.java

    -> Run Java program
        -> Syntax:
             java <ClassName>
        -> Example:
             java HelloWorld

    -> Run Java program with command-line arguments
        -> Syntax:
             java <ClassName> arg1 arg2 arg3
        -> Example:
             java HelloWorld Vinay Java

    -> Print all JVM system properties
        -> Syntax:
             java -XshowSettings:properties -version
        -> Example:
             java -XshowSettings:properties -version

    -> Print JVM configuration settings
        -> Syntax:
             java -XshowSettings:all -version
        -> Example:
             java -XshowSettings:all -version

    -> View bytecode generated by Java compiler
        -> Syntax:
             javap -c <ClassName>
        -> Example:
             javap -c HelloWorld

    -> View complete class information
        -> Syntax:
             javap -verbose <ClassName>
        -> Example:
             javap -verbose HelloWorld

    -> View public members only
        -> Syntax:
             javap -public <ClassName>
        -> Example:
             javap -public HelloWorld

    -> View private, protected and public members
        -> Syntax:
             javap -private <ClassName>
        -> Example:
             javap -private HelloWorld

    -> Launch JShell (Java REPL)
        -> Syntax:
             jshell
        -> Example:
             jshell

    -> Exit JShell
        -> Syntax:
             /exit

    -> Create executable JAR file
        -> Syntax:
             jar cfe <JarName.jar> <MainClass> *.class
        -> Example:
             jar cfe Hello.jar HelloWorld *.class

    -> Run executable JAR file
        -> Syntax:
             java -jar <JarName.jar>
        -> Example:
             java -jar Hello.jar

    -> List contents of a JAR file
        -> Syntax:
             jar tf <JarName.jar>
        -> Example:
             jar tf Hello.jar

    -> Extract JAR file contents
        -> Syntax:
             jar xf <JarName.jar>
        -> Example:
             jar xf Hello.jar

    -> Run a single Java source file (Java 11+)
        -> Syntax:
             java <FileName.java>
        -> Example:
             java HelloWorld.java

    -> Display Java help
        -> Syntax:
             java --help
        -> Example:
             java --help

    -> Display javac help
        -> Syntax:
             javac --help
        -> Example:
             javac --help

    -> Display all supported JVM options
        -> Syntax:
             java -X
        -> Example:
             java -X

    -> Display all JVM flags
        -> Syntax:
             java -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal -version
        -> Example:
             java -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal -version

    -> Display module information (Java 9+)
        -> Syntax:
             java --list-modules
        -> Example:
             java --list-modules


===============================================================================
=> Which Commands Work Only After Compilation?
===============================================================================

    Java source code (.java) cannot be understood directly by the JVM.

    Flow:

        .java Source File
                |
                | javac
                v
        .class Bytecode File
                |
                | JVM
                v
           Program Execution

    Therefore, some commands require an existing .class file and can
    only be executed after compilation.

    Examples:

    1. javap

        Purpose:
        -> Disassembles a .class file
        -> Shows constructors, methods, fields and bytecode

        Example:

            javac Employee.java
            javap Employee

        Why compilation is required?

        -> javap reads bytecode from Employee.class
        -> Without Employee.class there is nothing to inspect

    2. javap -c

        Purpose:
        -> Shows bytecode instructions

        Example:

            javac Employee.java
            javap -c Employee

        Why compilation is required?

        -> Bytecode exists only after javac creates .class file

    3. java Employee

        Purpose:
        -> Executes already compiled bytecode

        Example:

            javac Employee.java
            java Employee

        Why compilation is required?

        -> JVM executes Employee.class
        -> JVM cannot execute raw Java source code in this mode

    Rule:

        Any command that needs a .class file can run only after
        compilation.

        Examples:

            javap
            javap -c
            javap -v
            java ClassName

        (when running in normal compiled mode)


===============================================================================
=> How Does 'java File.java' Work Without Manual Compilation?
===============================================================================

    Starting from Java 11, Java introduced:

        Single-File Source-Code Execution

    Example:

        java Hello.java

    Many developers think:

        "Java is executing source code directly."

    This is NOT true.

    Internally Java still performs compilation.

    Actual Flow:

        Hello.java
             |
             | (Compiler invoked internally)
             v
        Temporary Bytecode
             |
             | (JVM executes)
             v
          Program Output

    Therefore:

        java Hello.java

    is roughly equivalent to:

        javac Hello.java
        java Hello

    except that Java performs the compilation automatically and
    manages the temporary bytecode itself.

===============================================================================
=> How To Verify That Java Is Compiling Internally?
===============================================================================

    Step 1:

        Create:

        Hello.java

        public class Hello {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                System.out.println("Hello");
            }
        }

    Step 2:

        Run:

            java Hello.java

        Output:

            Hello

    Step 3:

        Check directory contents.

            dir

        Observation:

            Hello.class is NOT present

    Conclusion:

        Java compiled the source code internally and used temporary
        bytecode instead of generating Hello.class in your folder.

===============================================================================
=> Strong Proof That Compilation Happens Internally
===============================================================================

    Create a file with a compilation error:

        public class Hello {
            public static void main(String[] args) {
                System.out.println("Hello")
            }
        }

    Missing semicolon.

    Run:

        java Hello.java

    Output:

        Compilation Error

    Observation:

        JVM reports compiler errors before execution starts.

    Conclusion:

        If compilation were not happening internally, Java would not
        be able to detect compile-time errors.

        Therefore:

            java File.java
                    =
            Internal Compilation
                    +
            Execution

===============================================================================
=> Interview Point
===============================================================================

    Question:

        Does Java execute source code directly when we run:

            java File.java ?

    Answer:

        No.

        Java still compiles the source file into bytecode first.
        Since Java 11, the compilation step is performed internally by
        the Java launcher, and the generated bytecode is executed
        immediately without creating a visible .class file in the
        current directory.
